<br>
You CANNOT have a game that gets significantly harder as you fight things more and more above your level without making things below your level utterly trivial.  That's just how it works.  If you have people with the power to take out their peers on the monster side, but cannot even think of taking out something much higher, they HAVE to be able to take out inferior members with little or no effort.<br>
<br>
Lemme put it this way:<br>
<br>
Player P can kill monster A because they are of similar strengths.  Player P cannot kill monster B because monster B is higher in level, is stronger, and would wipe the floor with player P.  This is set up to keep player P from achieving anything beyond his current station in life.  A month later, P has progressed to the point where he is of similar strength to monster B and can kill monster B (of course there is now an even bigger monster C on the horizon, but nevermind that).  Now that Player P is of similar strength to B, he is able to wipe the floor with monster A just as monster B would have done to him a month earlier, because that it what the difference between the two levels <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   intrinsically</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> means.<br>
<br>
In short, you cannot have a significant (exponential?) progression in strength without trivializing anything you would have fought in the past.  It cannot be done.  It does not work that way.  It is mathematically impossible.  That is why there is an artificial limit on Vox and Nag.<br>
<br>
I wouldn't be surprised if the main tank in my guild could go kill Nagafen with only a cleric backing him up.  That's because he HAS to be strong enough to fight in new world encounters, which are so far beyond Nagafen that it's like the difference between Nagafen and an orc pawn.<br>
<br>
